<bill id="DLM2901000" in.amend="false" irdnumbering="no" official="yes" xml:lang="en-NZ" year.imprint="2010" bill.no="134" bill.type="government" stage="2" year="2010">
  <billdetail>
    <title>New Zealand Public Health and Disability Amendment Bill</title>
    <billtype>Government Bill</billtype>
    <repnote>As reported from the Health Committee</repnote>
    <commentary id="DLM3242700" in.amend="false" irdnumbering="no" official="yes" bill.no="134" bill.type="government" stage="2" year="2010">
      <heading>Commentary</heading>
      <comm.lev1>
        <heading>Recommendation</heading>
        <para>
          <text>The Health Committee has examined the New Zealand Public Health and Disability Amendment Bill and recommends that it be passed with the amendments shown.</text>
        </para>
      </comm.lev1>
      <comm.lev1>
        <heading>Introduction</heading>
        <para>
          <text>This bill would amend the New Zealand Public Health and Disability Act 2000 in order to streamline the public health system. It seeks to improve the coordination of local, regional, and national planning, enhance the quality of health care, and reduce the duplication of corporate and administrative work. We received 13 submissions relating to the bill, all of which supported its intent.</text>
        </para>
      </comm.lev1>
      <comm.lev1>
        <heading>Commencement date</heading>
        <para>
          <text>We recommend the addition of proposed new subclause (2) in clause 2, which relates to the date on which the bill would come into force. As introduced, the bill provided for commencement by Order in Council to allow time for arrangements to be made relating to the establishment of the Health Quality and Safety Commission. We are concerned that the commencement clause in the bill as introduced could result in some or all of the legislation not being brought into force. Our proposed subsection provides that, if the bill or parts of the bill have not already been brought into force under subsection (1), it will come into force six months after the date on which it receives the Royal assent.</text>
        </para>
      </comm.lev1>
      <comm.lev1>
        <heading>Minister of Health’s power to give directions to all DHBs</heading>
        <para>
          <text>New section 33B, as inserted by clause 9, replicates section 107 of the Crown Entities Act 2004 and would grant the Minister of Health the power to direct district health boards to give effect to Government policy regarding</text>
          <list>
            <item>
              <label auto.number="no" denominator="no">•</label>
              <para>
                <text>collaborative planning across local, regional, and national boundaries</text>
              </para>
            </item>
            <item>
              <label auto.number="no" denominator="no">•</label>
              <para>
                <text>shared administration, support, and procurement services.</text>
              </para>
            </item>
          </list>
        </para>
        <para>
          <text>We recommend amending new section 33B(9) and inserting new section 33B(11), to clarify the application of the Crown Entities Act 2004 regarding the Minister’s directive power. New section 33B(9) would then provide that section 113 of the Crown Entities Act 2004 applies to a direction given under this section as if it were a ministerial direction given under that Act. This would limit the Minister’s powers to direct a Crown entity, or a member, employee, or office holder of a Crown entity.</text>
        </para>
        <para>
          <text>New section 33B(11) relates to section 115 of the Crown Entities Act 2004, which lays out the procedure required for consultation before the Minister gives a direction to a Crown entity. The addition of section 33B(11) would clarify that the procedure detailed in the new section 33B should be used for giving directions, rather than the procedure in the Crown Entities Act 2004.</text>
        </para>
      </comm.lev1>
      <comm.lev1>
        <heading>Commencement of the planning framework</heading>
        <para>
          <text>New section 38(1)(a) (inserted by clause 10) relates to the requirement that the Minister direct every DHB to prepare a plan for each financial year. We recommend amending new section 38(1)(a) to change the date from 1 July 2012 to 1 July 2011 so that the new planning framework could be implemented during the 2011/12 planning round.</text>
        </para>
        <para>
          <text>Consequential amendments would be required to remove references to specific types of plan. New clauses 8A, 8B, 8C, and 8D would provide this consistency.</text>
        </para>
        <comm.lev2>
          <heading>DHB public consultation requirements</heading>
          <para>
            <text>Some of us are concerned that the bill would remove requirements for DHBs to consult the public during the planning process. Section 92(1)(g) (clause 16) of the bill as introduced should provide the power to make regulations that would apply to plans. Most of us are satisfied that the regulations could impose sufficient procedural requirements, including consultation.</text>
          </para>
        </comm.lev2>
      </comm.lev1>
      <comm.lev1>
        <heading>Health Quality and Safety Commission</heading>
        <para>
          <text>We recommend inserting new section 59AB to define the objectives of the Health Quality and Safety Commission in leading and coordinating work across the health and disability sector. The commission’s objectives would be to monitor and improve the quality and safety of health and disability support services, and to help providers in the health and disability sector to make such improvements.</text>
        </para>
        <para>
          <text>We recommend amending new section 59B in clause 11, which defines the functions of the Health Quality and Safety Commission, to include some that were previously undertaken by the National Health Epidemiology and Quality Assurance Advisory Committee. New clause 6 would repeal section 17 of the principal Act, which sets out the powers and objectives of the National Health Epidemiology and Quality Assurance Advisory Committee. The functions of the Health Quality and Safety Commission would include </text>
          <list>
            <item>
              <label auto.number="no" denominator="no">•</label>
              <para>
                <text>providing advice to the Minister on health epidemiology, quality assurance, mortality, and how to improve quality and safety</text>
              </para>
            </item>
            <item>
              <label auto.number="no" denominator="no">•</label>
              <para>
                <text>determining quality and safety indicators</text>
              </para>
            </item>
            <item>
              <label auto.number="no" denominator="no">•</label>
              <para>
                <text>providing public reports on quality and safety</text>
              </para>
            </item>
            <item>
              <label auto.number="no" denominator="no">•</label>
              <para>
                <text>promoting and supporting better quality and safety</text>
              </para>
            </item>
            <item>
              <label auto.number="no" denominator="no">•</label>
              <para>
                <text>disseminating information about quality and safety</text>
              </para>
            </item>
            <item>
              <label auto.number="no" denominator="no">•</label>
              <para>
                <text>undertaking any other function that relates to quality and safety or that it is authorised to perform by the Minister following consultation.</text>
              </para>
            </item>
          </list>
        </para>
        <para>
          <text>We recommend the addition of new section 59B(1A) to require that the Health Quality and Safety Commission, when appropriate, work with the Ministry of Health, the Health and Disability Commissioner, service providers, health professionals, consumers, and other stakeholders. </text>
        </para>
        <para>
          <text>We recommend amending the wording of new section 5(7A) in clause 4 so that the description of the Health Quality and Safety Commission’s functions is consistent with new sections 59A to 59D in clause 11.</text>
        </para>
        <comm.lev2>
          <heading>Mortality review committees</heading>
          <para>
            <text>We recommend the insertion of new clause 6 to repeal section 18 of the Act, and that the additional new section 59D in clause 11 of the bill as introduced be adopted. Section 18 of the Act enables the Minister to appoint one or more mortality review committees, and sets out the objectives, powers, and functions of the committees. New section 59D in clause 11 would allow the Health Quality and Safety Commission, rather than the Minister, to appoint mortality review committees. The objectives, powers, and functions of mortality review committees would remain the same. This amendment would necessitate the adoption of new clause 17A to maintain consistency.</text>
          </para>
        </comm.lev2>
      </comm.lev1>
      <comm.lev1>
        <heading>Other amendments</heading>
        <para>
          <text>Our proposed changes to the wording of the sections 33A(1), 33A(2), 33A(6)(a), and 33B(1) in clause 9 would ensure that the terminology was consistent with that of the Act.</text>
        </para>
        <para>
          <text>The amendments we recommend to new sections 33A and 33B in clause 9 would mean that sections 22(1) and 22(2) would require minor amendments for consistency.</text>
        </para>
        <para>
          <text>We recommend amending new section 39(1) in clause 10 to clarify the wording relating to Ministerial directions. The recommended amendment to new section 41 makes the section clearer to read, but does not change the information it conveys.</text>
        </para>
        <para>
          <text>We recommend a minor amendment to section 66 of the Act to be effected by new clause 13. The amendment would repeal and replace subsection 1 as most of the paragraphs to which it originally applied have been repealed.</text>
        </para>
        <para>
          <text>We recommend inserting new clause 14A to correct a grammatical error.</text>
        </para>
      </comm.lev1>
      <comm.appendix>
        <heading>Appendix</heading>
        <comm.lev2>
          <heading>Committee process</heading>
          <para>
            <text>The New Zealand Public Health and Disability Amendment Bill was referred to us on 19 May 2010. The closing date for submissions was 18 June 2010. We received and considered 13 submissions from interested groups and individuals and heard evidence from five of them.</text>
          </para>
          <para>
            <text>We received advice from the Ministry of Health, and we received a report from the Regulations Review Committee on clause 2.</text>
          </para>
        </comm.lev2>
        <comm.lev2>
          <heading>Committee membership</heading>
          <para>
            <text>Dr Paul Hutchison (Chairperson)</text>
          </para>
          <para>
            <text>Dr Jackie Blue</text>
          </para>
          <para>
            <text>Hon Ruth Dyson</text>
          </para>
          <para>
            <text>Kevin Hague</text>
          </para>
          <para>
            <text>Hon Luamanuvao Winnie Laban</text>
          </para>
          <para>
            <text>Iain Lees-Galloway</text>
          </para>
          <para>
            <text>Eric Roy</text>
          </para>
          <para>
            <text>Nicky Wagner</text>
          </para>
          <para>
            <text>Michael Woodhouse</text>
          </para>
          <para>
            <text/>
          </para>
        </comm.lev2>
      </comm.appendix>
    </commentary>
  </billdetail>
